Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Stabilizer Formalism: Overview", "TechNoteSection",
 CellTags->"Section14",
 CellID->1424127932,ExpressionUUID->"62e45f64-7144-4fa0-866d-8e3d649f571a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A quantum error-correction code encodes quantum states of a fixed number of \
qubits in a subspace of the Hilbert space of more qubits. This subspace is \
called the ",
 StyleBox["code space",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " of the particular code. The code space is specified by the logical basis \
states (called ",
 StyleBox["codewords",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ") spanning it. "
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1612907309,ExpressionUUID->"114022ba-8464-4038-824d-1ddc9d968749"],

Cell["\<\
A natural way to analyze the code is to inspect how the quantum states in the \
code space are affected by the errors. Mathematically, this is achieved by \
examining the evolution of the quantum states under the quantum operation \
describing the error process. This corresponds to the usual \
Schr\[ODoubleDot]dinger picture of dynamical processes in quantum mechanics.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->447066282,ExpressionUUID->"f7137734-aa39-49e1-9a5c-f3ad146a2f7c"],

Cell["\<\
It may sound odd at first glance, but a code space can also be specified by \
operators that preserve it, and that is the goal of stabilizer formalism. In \
a broad sense, it is analogous to the Heisenberg picture of dynamical \
processes in quantum mechanics.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1945204368,ExpressionUUID->"fa7d89b7-fb90-4f5a-9ca6-ac5314fa8974"],

Cell["\<\
To get an idea about the tasks to be established in stabilizer formalism, it \
is convenient to examine the effects of extreme classes of general quantum \
operations, unitary gates and measurements.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1906254695,ExpressionUUID->"b97f0bc0-14ba-4e7b-9230-c814076c1bc4"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Unitary Gates", "Subsection",
 CellTags->"Section15",
 CellID->114129272,ExpressionUUID->"f17aa83c-e70b-4cf8-86f9-7969b3337087"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Consider a unitary operation ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["U", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "37cb0ce7-09d2-4958-9dc1-016ffb595424"],
 " on a quantum system, and suppose that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[ScriptCapitalS]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7a50d070-c78f-405c-a071-ce1717d1ac54"],
 " stabilizes a given subspace ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[ScriptCapitalV]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4f32e639-f993-41f6-a6f9-de89d49a0df5"],
 ". The unitary operation ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["U", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a429643e-75a6-46bf-a74c-cb55e9a515a2"],
 " transforms ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[ScriptCapitalV]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5d1831c7-8833-419c-8cd1-2e275417cdc8"],
 " onto ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"U", " ", "\[ScriptCapitalV]", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d8eb2370-fd3f-4d40-b60a-e029d850755c"],
 ", and in general, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[ScriptCapitalS]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "797ba348-d566-457f-ba5a-3e20953f6822"],
 " does not stabilizes the new subspace any longer. Then, what is the \
stabilizer of the new subspace ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"U", " ", "\[ScriptCapitalV]", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e91a46c8-7e03-48ae-8419-1d5d1483e8ec"],
 "?"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->467777733,ExpressionUUID->"ffe8707e-b9ac-4839-9ef9-3bac81d1f93f"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Suppose that an operator ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["G", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ec5a0776-1a0d-46fb-a990-e691a8900283"],
 " is an element of the stabilizer ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[ScriptCapitalS]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "93c7ae19-0008-4d2a-8e70-0bf19088b929"],
 ". Then, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"G", 
     TemplateBox[{"\[Psi]"},
      "Ket"]}], "=", 
    TemplateBox[{"\[Psi]"},
     "Ket"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d450f7bd-e72a-4b5a-b55a-edb5d1c036cc"],
 " for any quantum state ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[{"\[Psi]"},
    "Ket"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "0f3036e5-bdc6-493f-be9a-91bfdbc85517"],
 " in the subspace ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[ScriptCapitalV]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c0a19ac2-d777-49a3-ac89-b0ae3979dac8"],
 ". We observe that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"U", " ", "G", " ", 
     SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"], "U", 
     TemplateBox[{"\[Psi]"},
      "Ket"]}], "=", 
    RowBox[{"U", 
     TemplateBox[{"\[Psi]"},
      "Ket"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c6860699-0510-4231-b811-38bd16a8b90b"],
 ". This means that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"U", " ", "G", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "8b4e19de-1931-4f9d-9510-5e4344b78ef4"],
 " stabilizes ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"U", 
    TemplateBox[{"\[Psi]"},
     "Ket"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1e671fb5-6051-46ca-8af7-f0c6b59cd451"],
 ", and hence the whole subspace ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"U", " ", "\[ScriptCapitalV]"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4bad7af7-2ccb-4878-b5d1-92a263216f0b"],
 ". In other words, the group ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"U", " ", "\[ScriptCapitalS]", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1670f8c5-3258-492a-ab57-6f7e04bccf50"],
 " is the stabilizer of the new subspace ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"U", " ", "\[ScriptCapitalV]"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b8e6d682-d55e-4ddb-ad0a-d7f1aee4f5b1"],
 ". Now, suppose that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    SubscriptBox["G", "j"], "}"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "75fef497-5e17-40a1-b617-addc72ef7b8c"],
 " is a generating set of stabilizer ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[ScriptCapitalS]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "10d2ff38-7067-4b8b-a332-575221a49dc0"],
 ". Since any element of \[ScriptCapitalS] is generated by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["G", "j"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "0ddfcb41-efcc-4c61-9c61-7d45bf82996c"],
 ", any operator of the form ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"U", " ", "G", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "68880725-6422-4190-a884-adc53dcfd3c9"],
 " for ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"G", "\[Element]", "\[ScriptCapitalS]"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"9323a4ce-5a92-42a7-9b9e-e2977e22c754"],
 " is generated by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"U", " ", 
    SubscriptBox["G", "j"], " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "fd5d2496-5edd-4d2f-910a-1dadec9e9925"],
 ". That is, the new stabilizer ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"U", " ", "\[ScriptCapitalS]", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "9ba2fc35-feca-4ab7-8542-0c62647a83bb"],
 " is generated by ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"U", " ", 
    SubscriptBox["G", "j"], " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d2536cf0-068d-438b-b2d2-b26aa77d31cc"],
 ". To sum up, under a unitary operation ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["U", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "143ba3b9-3888-4dd0-838d-1078d2c6d796"],
 ", the generators ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["G", "j"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "11f636ae-d614-4635-b4a1-fe327a7c2f0a"],
 " of the stabilizer are transformed as ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["G", "j"], "\[RightTeeArrow]", 
    RowBox[{"U", " ", 
     SubscriptBox["G", "j"], 
     SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "a8b3a4c1-02a9-47c4-a377-320d1ed2837d"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->2726864,ExpressionUUID->"a19c8a02-3df9-4cad-998c-3802298931f8"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "As the unitary operation ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["U", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "088d7c9b-f7ca-4c78-a18a-b8beac240c9f"],
 " changes logical basis states, the logical Pauli operators must accordingly \
transform. Following the above line of arguments for the generators of the \
stabilizer, we see that the logical Pauli operators also transform in the \
same manner, ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["X", "j"], "\[RightTeeArrow]", 
    RowBox[{"U", " ", 
     SubscriptBox["X", "j"], 
     SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "e575dc52-2a6a-4e24-87b7-685812b0f2ab"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["Z", "j"], "\[RightTeeArrow]", 
    RowBox[{"U", " ", 
     SubscriptBox["Z", "j"], 
     SuperscriptBox["U", "\[Dagger]"]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "cde37d30-d8e3-4535-8dc7-e12d8d817339"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->733246661,ExpressionUUID->"8433fd6f-c28e-46f1-aefa-fff4e47cd34d"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Measurements", "Subsection",
 CellTags->"Section16",
 CellID->1415464941,ExpressionUUID->"3ccbb8df-4f8a-41bc-9c8c-1ef5fea14f3d"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Consider an observable ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["M", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "d0868614-9e12-46cb-be3e-46352846964e"],
 " on a quantum system, and suppose that ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[ScriptCapitalS]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4079769a-9e0f-4af2-a333-513a501ded96"],
 " stabilizes a given subspace ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[ScriptCapitalV]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "64665835-52a5-4971-8487-e2b909de3815"],
 ". After the measurement of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["M", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "7ed74eab-28b8-4fab-9db0-88e29d60a5b9"],
 ", subspace ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["\[ScriptCapitalV]", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "0c6cc4b6-9649-44ef-bcd7-05a0c45935a1"],
 " is projected onto onto ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["P", "m"], "\[ScriptCapitalV]"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"ce781433-87de-4e49-9cad-43a5a8cd9183"],
 ", where ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["P", "m"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "64fe47c7-6cd2-4999-b937-eb036e55f448"],
 " is the projection onto the eigenspace belonging to eigenvalue ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["m", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ad15d904-6d80-43a3-b13e-11579a605b60"],
 " of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["M", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "4310bd7e-1634-43a5-953c-62b63ea3ad45"],
 "."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->2042905568,ExpressionUUID->"96428e8b-1344-41ac-ad18-a8685baa31f5"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Now, we ask a similar question as in the above, that is, what is the \
stabilizer of the new subspace ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["P", "m"], "\[ScriptCapitalV]"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"7e24a9a2-0d2d-40c8-aff0-2cd3967f80a1"],
 "? Unlike the case of unitary gates, it is in general highly nontrivial to \
find the stabilizer of the new subspace not to speak of expressing the new \
generators in terms of original generators. Finding new logical Pauli \
operators associated with the new subspace is also tedious because without \
establishing an explicit relation between the new and initial stabilizer, one \
has to find the local operators from the scratch."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1145333140,ExpressionUUID->"c841f6a1-1c2d-4e8e-9cef-4e9668a6c073"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Benefits from Restriction", "Subsection",
 CellTags->"Section17",
 CellID->1718155919,ExpressionUUID->"2eac35cf-89cf-4a40-8a39-5b9d712d6a62"],

Cell["\<\
So far, the discussion has been completely general. However, for many quantum \
information processing procedures including quantum error correction, the \
Pauli operators and their tensor products are sufficient. Therefore, it would \
be useful to focus on unitary operators  the conjugation by which transforms \
the tensor products of single-qubit Pauli operators to such products. In this \
case, stabilizer formalism turns out to be extremely simple and insightful.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1981413071,ExpressionUUID->"60b1d6a8-9d76-4779-87a9-19f3cbb723d5"],

Cell["\<\
As a matter fact, in this case, describing quantum operations by tracking the \
stabilizer is far more (i.e., exponentially) efficient than tracking the \
subspace or quantum states. This is why stabilizer formalism is so powerful.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->580570268,ExpressionUUID->"258c5ca9-249e-4461-a500-28de2274c980"]
}, Open  ]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The Pauli and Clifford Groups", "TechNoteSection",
 CellTags->"Section18",
 CellID->1626285955,ExpressionUUID->"ad5dcf62-4726-470f-bbb1-3f1128f39940"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "In general, finding the stabilizer of a given subspace and vice versa may \
be non-trivial. Fortunately, when operators are restricted to the Pauli \
operators or their tensor products on a fixed number ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["n", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "753a65cc-1724-44bf-a1c1-09b3711d2fcf"],
 " of qubits, the stabilizers have particularly simple structures and useful \
properties. Moreover, in accordance with the discretization of errors, such \
operators are enough to describe any quantum noise operation. Therefore, it \
is useful to restrict the parent group of any stabilizer to the Pauli group. \
This naturally restricts the allowed unitary transformations to the Clifford \
group as well."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1963670316,ExpressionUUID->"ead1f338-858f-43c0-a377-2fa95c864d65"],

Cell["\<\
The Pauli group is the group of all tensor products of single-qubit Pauli \
operators. The elements of the Pauli group are called (multi-qubit) Pauli \
operators. The Clifford group is the group of all unitary operators that keep \
the Pauli group invariant (that is, map a Pauli operator to another Pauli \
operator) under conjugation. The elements of the Clifford group are called \
Clifford operators.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->878313916,ExpressionUUID->"adf90746-668b-4edd-9847-0207a20d6e67"],

Cell["\<\
Properties of the Pauli and Clifford groups are explained in detail in \
another document, the Pauli and Clifford Groups. Here we summarises some \
properties directly related to stabilizer formalism.\
\>", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->19396734,ExpressionUUID->"4de75f51-4e71-4962-a991-4119915b03d3"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["The Pauli Group", "Subsection",
 CellTags->"Section11",
 CellID->1730877641,ExpressionUUID->"354c8359-7b43-4e11-bdfd-dd0c971f5e96"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The ",
 StyleBox[ButtonBox["full Pauli group",
  BaseStyle->"Link",
  ButtonData->"paclet:QuantumMob/Q3/ref/FullPauliGroup"],
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    OverscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalP]", "~"], "(", "n", ")"}], 
   TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"d861081e-58c1-44c9-ae7c-bd1ec840a5da"],
 " on ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["n", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "57cd82cc-472d-43c5-8b0d-d9b27a57bc0c"],
 " qubits consists of tensor products of single-qubit Pauli operators ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["I", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ae69861c-81d8-4474-ba5f-d5ce2b31d7dc"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["X", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "b822b974-c16d-4538-b591-939cd978179f"],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["Y", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "5f16e594-d28e-419a-bb93-eedd557d5fd4"],
 ", and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox["Z", TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "93d333fe-7499-4bad-a2b1-4c16c68d2b6d"],
 " associated with the 2\[Times]2 matrices"
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1047030025,ExpressionUUID->"e6afc1c7-b044-4d17-aaef-e7d7c3d523ad"],

Cell[TextData[Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"I", "=", 
    RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
       {"1", "0"},
       {"0", "1"}
      }], ")"}]}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"X", "=", 
    RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
       {"0", "1"},
       {"1", "0"}
      }], ")"}]}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Y", "=", 
    RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
       {"0", 
        RowBox[{"-", "\[ImaginaryI]"}]},
       {"\[ImaginaryI]", "0"}
      }], ")"}]}], ",", " ", 
   RowBox[{"Z", "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"(", GridBox[{
        {"1", "0"},
        {"0", 
         RowBox[{"-", "1"}]}
       }], ")"}], "."}]}]}], 
  TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->"beee12eb-4ec4-42cd-9033-5b37a918aa4f"]], \
"DisplayMath",
 CellID->952626657,ExpressionUUID->"080e47fd-c835-41ab-aff5-e55bf1ba4351"],

Cell["Enlisting the elements, it is given by", "TechNoteText",
 CellID->1305635814,ExpressionUUID->"56c3d03f-8fa2-4bd5-a101-117690ceabb2"],

Cell[TextData[{
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     OverscriptBox["\[ScriptCapitalP]", "~"], "(", "n", ")"}], "=", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "1"}], ",", 
       RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "\[ImaginaryI]"}]}], "}"}], "\[Times]", 
     SuperscriptBox[
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"I", ",", "X", ",", "Y", ",", "Z"}], "}"}], 
      RowBox[{"\[CircleTimes]", "n"}]]}]}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "1239476a-eb1b-4dab-8e0b-9a26c09b5c4a"],
 "."
}], "DisplayMath",
 CellID->833220852,ExpressionUUID->"20203b4b-a417-4d1f-aebd-a149b81963eb"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The additional phase factors ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "1"}], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "418abd72-9c11-4819-bee2-76368f56d4c9"],
 " and ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "\[ImaginaryI]"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"e2d5ac0b-0246-4292-9f99-21e51028cedd"],
 " are required because the product of two Pauli operators gives another \
Pauli operator accompanied by factor ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"\[PlusMinus]", "\[ImaginaryI]"}], TraditionalForm]],
  ExpressionUUID->"99638d40-c670-472e-9c37-e105b8585b9d"],
 ". Otherwise, the underlying set is not closed under the group \
multiplication."
}], "TechNoteText",
 CellID->201997477,ExpressionUUID->"1e05ebe6-d815-416a-a9e6-3d6c55312a55"],

